  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering is a serious crime with significant penalties. The specific consequences can vary depending on the circumstances, but generally include:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Potential prison sentences of up to 20 years\n- Substantial financial fines, often hundreds of thousands of dollars\n- Potential forfeitures of assets involved in the laundering\n\n2. Additional Potential Consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Asset seizure\n\nThe exact penalties depend on factors like the amount of money involved, specific circumstances of the offense, and whether it's a first-time or repeat offense. Federal prosecutors typically use statutes like the Money Laundering Control Act to pursue these cases.\n\nFor precise details about a specific situation, I recommend consulting a qualified criminal defense attorney who specializes in federal financial crimes.",
